  					<td align=center valign="top" width=100%><br>
  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - BARD</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>BARD KITING</font> - <small>Divamaru Silverlight, Torvonnilous</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>Bards can do a little of everything, right? Well, it's mostly true. We /are/ the best addition to any party out there. Unfortunately, this limits our soloing capacity. We don't have the hit points and combat skills of the melee classes, nor pets, nor (until higher levels) roots and charms.
<p>
However, bards are the only class I've discovered that can, starting at 12th level, solo yellows and low reds without ever taking a point of damage or expending any mana. The technique of Bard kiting is unique in that respect, and is a useful tool for all bards to have.
<p>
Kiting is a technique where you damage your enemy from afar so that they cannot damage you back. Most of the time, this involves an immobilization spell (such as Root or Snare) to hold the mob in place while the kiter blasts them with spells or has a pet attack them. Bards, however, kite differently, and the two-spell combo to do this with is Selo's Accelerando and Brusco's Boastful Bellow, or simply 'Selo-Bellow'.
<p>
The technique is rather simple. Place your drum in your hand. (It is possible to do this without the drum, but I prefer the extra speed as a safety margin.) Find a mob you wish to kite. Make sure you are in an open area with room to run and, hopefully, in an area where you won't attract the attention of other mobs wandering by. Start your speed song. Once you're moving faster, hit the mob with a Bellow to pull it. The mob will begin to chase you.
<p>
Now, simply run in circles. Twist Selo and then two Bellows. Selo-Bellow-Bellow. Selo-Bellow-Bellow. Repeat until the mob expires. If you've done this right and had a bit of luck, you'll never have been touched.
<p>
There are some drawbacks to this technique. First, it takes a LONG time to kill something, especially if its yellow or red to you. But it's a tradeoff to having no downtime between kills. Secondly, you will miss notes from time to time. This is especially bad if your missed notes cause you to loose the Selo's effect and the mob can catch up with you. When in doubt, always keep Selo's going. Thirdly, this is rather amusing for outsiders to watch. I've caused more laughter in West Commonlands hunting kodiaks at 12th level with this technique. Further, these people often don't understand that you're kiting, and may think you're running for help. They will then leap into the fray to kill your target, thinking they are helping you, when in fact, you're in no danger at all. This accidental kill-stealing should be something you expect will happen from time to time. Try not to be too upset when it happens. Fourthly, sometimes a mob will land a hit on you. The worst result of this is that you might get stunned. This means that your songs end, and you are frozen in place for the mob to get some free hits. If this happens, get Selo's going again ASAP and run out of the mob's range. Get your bearings, then start kiting it again.
<p>
Selo-Bellow is a valuable technique for those times when you cannot find a group. It is time-consuming, it is repetative, but it's also rather impressive. There's nothing quite like taking down a low red mob and not having a scratch to show for it.
<p>
Good hunting!<br>
Divamaru Silverlight<br>
Torvonnilous
</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'>&nbsp;</td></tr>
